> @aleksei-fedotov in the case that a follow-on collaborator is called with a context and the first-to-arrive doesn't bail out prematurely, the behavior would be that the follow-on collaborator ignores its context, correct?

The context of first-to-arrive call is expected to be used for all collaborators. Overall, it seems strange if different contexts are used (or some threads do not specify the context). (P.S. I believe you wanted to notify @alexey-katranov).

As for exception vs cancellation, consider the following serial example:
```
try {
    bool zero_element_found = false;
    for (auto v : container) {
        if (!v.ptr) {
            throw bad_element;                         // exception on error
        }
        if (*v.ptr == 0) {
            zero_element_found = true;
            break;                                     // cancelation on normal program flow condition
        }
    }
    if (zero_element_found) { ... }
} catch ( ... ) {
    // report error
}
```
The main issue that neither exception nor cancelation will not work as expected in a threaded application because the both cancelation and exception are local to the executing thread. While the `break` condition is semi working because threads that met the condition will save some cycles, the exception condition can be dangerous because the exception will be thrown on some other thread that might miss sending a signal about the completion to the main thread.

oneTBB provides mechanisms to handle the both situations. The exception condition is handled automatically that any exception is captured and rethrown on the waiting thread, so it works like the exception occurs on the waiting thread. To improve the performance, the exception propagation mechanism triggers the cancelation mechanism that sets the flag into `tbb::task_group_context` that any not currently running task associated with this context should be skipped. However, we do not need to work with context (only to request the cancelation), i.e. the example can be transformed to parallel execution in the following way:
```
try {
    std::atomic<bool> zero_element_found = false;
    parallel_for (auto v : container) {
        if (!v.ptr) {
            throw bad_element;                         // exception on error
        }
        if (*v.ptr == 0) {
            zero_element_found = true;
            tbb::task::current_context()->cancel_group_execution();  // cancelation on normal program flow condition
         }
    }
    if (zero_element_found) { ... }
} catch ( ... ) {
    // report error
}
```
So, in some cases, you do not need to pass `task_group_context` explicitly to a functor or parallel algorithm.

The same idea can be applied to `collaborative_call_once` that any exception is processed like in a serial code and cancelation can be explicitly requested if necessary.

As `std::call_once` it has serial semantics and cancelation is not really required (user can use their own flags if necessary).

